segments.text: He understood what the mission of Student Affairs was all about and was able to put most of that in practice while he was here.
Because when he was, he really started the Division of Student Affairs, or Student Services back then it was called, at Texas A&M University.
And he still refers to a paper that he wrote at Christmas time in 1973 about what his goals were for the division.
And over time, he put almost every one of them in place.
Now, he came here only a few months before you did, didn't he?
He was here about two or three months before I was.
That's right.
Okay.
What he put into place, well, in the long run, recreational sportsmen made it to student affairs.
That took a few years.
But he started the personal counseling center, which is now called the student counseling center.
That didn't exist at that time.
He brought it in.
the health center over to him.
At one time the police were in student affairs.
Student financial aid he brought into student affairs.
There's a lot of things that he wrote about in that paper that happened over the next 10 years.
By 83 most of those things are in place.
And then describe McCandless personality.
Charles McCandless was
energetic, bright, always had a smile on his face.
He's the best customer, one of the best.
We have several long-term customers.
But he started playing handball and racquetball with Buck Henderson.
Buck was a student and Charles was the director of intramurals.
And I'm not sure what year that was, but it was probably in the early 60s.
Well, they still play three times a week.

Charles, this was after Charles left here to be the vice president of Iowa State, retired, came back, became a member again, and now they're playing again, but great customer, great friend, and very bright.
You know, he's always fun to be around because he's always got a good story.
In those early years, did you run into any obstacles as intramurals was growing?
No, it was interesting because we were growing so fast.
We were growing by almost 100.
About four years in a row, our major team sports were growing from 100 to 200, 300 to 400 teams.
It was expanding that rapidly.
What happened to us is we would run out of money in April or May.
And what I had to do is write a letter to Dr. Coles and say, this is what we budgeted for, this is what we've experienced.
We were out of money, can you help us?
And he was able to help us.
No, there really were no major obstacles.
The people we worked with, from Dr. Lamas to Dr. Coles, the presidents that were in place, were always very supportive.
In that time, we built the original Penberthy Fields here, and then we built another set of fields that are now called Penberthy Intramural Sports Center.
We built the Reed Building.
And that was primarily Carl Landis' project and then we built this village.
So we haven't had a lack of support.
In those years when there was rapid growth, the expenses were for what, referees?
Primarily for referees.
Where did you get those officials?
Same place we get them now.
We advertise.
All of our officials are students.

What we try to accomplish, and probably are as good at this as anybody, is taking somebody who's never officiated a game, and that's 75% of our people in every sport, every year, never officiated before, and put them through a training program that gives them an opportunity to be successful at officiating.
That's one of the toughest jobs there is.
But that's our approach to it and that's the way we've done that.
We employ right now 1,100 different students a year.
About 500 of those are officials.
Now what was the compensation for them in the early years and what is it now?
Now they're starting at about $5.25 an hour.
Back then, the minimum wage, you may have to help me with this, the minimum wage was probably $2 or $2.50 an hour, somewhere there.
So it's normally been minimum wage?
Right now, they're just a little bit above minimum wage.
But for most of the years I've been here, officials have been paid minimum wage.
Describe the shift that must have occurred as intramurals went from being predominantly core to, I presume, predominantly non-core.
It was a pretty smooth transition in reality.
The student body at the time I got here was predominantly non-reported.
There was probably 2,000 in the Corps and 16,000 in the Army.
But back then, there was some fairly sharp divides, as you can imagine.
And you had Corps non-reqs, is what they called them.
And we did some scheduling that...
that helped them really compete against each other in a more pleasant way.
And I think in time it became Aggies, you know, the one competition with Aggies as opposed to Corps versus none or any kind of deal.
But the transition really went pretty smooth.
Were there ever any incidents that you remember in the Corps, non-Corps?
There was some pretty healthy competition, but really no incidents.
Our students here, when you put them in a competitive situation, follow the rules.
They don't hassle the officials.
It's one of the best competitive situations you'll ever see.
They're good sports.
Who did the training of the new officials?
That was me to begin with, and then I had an assistant director my first year here, Jim Peter, and he took that job over, and then John Meyer, who's now in Colorado.
But it's always been, as I always say,
We've had anywhere from one to four people in our intramural program.
And their primary job is training.
They have to be good teachers.
They have to know their sports.
They have to know the rules.
But the primary thing is they have to know how to teach, because they're teaching people a job skill.
Which would be, were the easiest and the most difficult officials to locate?
Volleyball is the easiest.
And we, in Texas, have a good supply of women playing volleyball in high school.
They understand the sport very well.
And they're willing to officiate.
And softball is fairly easy to officiate, too.
The ones that are most difficult is basketball.
I mean, it's the hardest sport to officiate.
Even though there's a lot of people playing it, there's not many people that really want to call off any.
And everybody's so close together in that game.
Football is tough because everybody thinks they know football until they try to officiate it, and then they realize how little they know about the game.
Rules in football are a little more difficult than they are in the other sports, and they're more difficult to enforce.
Right.
In those early years, as you looked at what we were doing and not doing, are there any that you thought that we should have been doing that we were not?
Are you surprised we weren't?

I was a little concerned when I first got here that the way we were supervising recreation, drop-in recreation, and the way we were securing facilities and managing facilities for the safety of the participants.
That was one of the recommendations I made to Dr. Landis.

And that's really what he was looking for, because from somebody who had been involved in physical education and not necessarily managing facilities, that's kind of what he was looking for, somebody to say, we really need to do this.
Any sports that you added?
we've had just about every sport that you can imagine here.
That's the thing that's fun about it.
It's creative.
You go to conferences, you find new sports, you introduce them here, and they work.
Some examples.
Well, flickerball is an Aggie sport.
You won't see that anyplace else.
Flicker?
Is that one word or two?
Two words.
Actually, it's one word, flickerball.
And that's a football passing game.
But after you catch the ball, you have to stop.
You can't run with the ball.
So it's a football passing game, and it's a combination of football skills and basketball skills.
Pass the ball, catch the ball, and you end up throwing it through a target, a goal.
A board that looks like a basketball backboard, but it's got a hole in the center of it.
It goes through, you score three points.
If you hit the ball, you score one point.
So it has soccer kind of skills, basketball kind of skills, and football skills.
Is it a round ball or a, oh it's a football, okay.
You're throwing a football.
And that's an Aggie game.
That one's been most popular for many years.
It's pretty well died out now.
It's, the primary reason it's died out is it's a really difficult game to officiate.
You can't find anybody to officiate if they want to.
Inner tube water sports, that was pretty interesting.
Inner tube water polo and inner tube water basketball.
It took a game that's really tough to play, put people in inner tubes and they have a lot of fun with it.
So that was a pretty good one.
Pickleball is a game played with a wooden paddle and a wiffle ball over a badminton net that's on a badminton court, but the badminton net is lowered down to like a tennis net.
It's called pickleball.
some really strange.
Look and see if there's any others that I can't think of right off the top of my head.
One of the things we're doing now is fantasy football.
So it's not it's not an active sport.
But it's, it's very much sports related fantasy footballs.
indoor soccer.
That, gosh, last year we had 197 teams in indoor soccer.
Played on a basketball arena?
Yeah.
When you look at it into our facility area, our indoor soccer court is about 208 feet long and about 85 feet wide.
But it's got boards like an ice arena.
But when you got here from the University of Texas, as you looked at the array of things we were doing, are there some that we were not, that you were a little surprised we weren't doing?
No, it was a fairly broad program.
You know, I think the main thing that we added was women's leagues and co-ed leagues.
And then a few years later we added the skill levels.
And that really made a big difference.
The things that we didn't really have a handle on was facility supervision for free play, sports clubs,
There really was no organizational structure for sports clubs and that's something I started about two years after I got here and got funding through Dr. Cole to support.
Outdoor recreation was being managed by a committee at the Student Center and in time that came over to us.
But that one, we had to play the politics right, so we didn't take it away from them.
They ended up saying, here it is.
But we went from an intramural program to a comprehensive recreational sports program.
And part of that was, when I got here, I knew two things.
Sports clubs and facility management, we had to do.
And that's from my experience in Texas.
And then over the years of going to
participating in our national associations.
You know, you pick up on things that you could be, should be doing.
Now, the athletic director on paper when you arrived, I guess, was Emory Ballard.
Correct.
In fact, who in the athletic department did you work with most?
Marvin Tate.
Marvin, who was at that time associate, I believe.
Right.
And was that pleasant, easy?
Yeah.
Marvin was good to work with.
Of course, he later became Mayor Bryan.
He was a good politician.
He took care of himself first, his programs first, but he was not unwilling to help us whenever we needed help.
We started one of the first, we call it varsity level two programs in the country, where we elevated water polo into a varsity status without scholarship.
It was kind of a division three.
model program within a Division I program.
It's kind of unusual.
We did that with soccer and with, so we did some creative things with Marvin.
He was willing to work with us.
All right.
Then he became athletic director, in fact, in about 77 or 8.
So did you continue to work with him or was there a subordinate?
We probably started working with Walter Groff more after Marvin became the director.
All right.
And then did, as the football, head football coach changed, did that cause any trouble, any change for you all?
Not really because the two, you know, the people that have been here for most of the time I've been here,
Billy Picker is the facility manager for the athletic department, and Wally Groff has been there the whole time.
And we still communicate with those two people most of the time.
Describe some of the realities of the expansion of the women's involvement in intramurals.
There must have been some unique experiences occasionally.
Well, that's a pretty good question.
Okay.
They explode in numbers, I presume, don't they?
Yeah, the numbers grew pretty rapidly.
I guess the one thing that was kind of exciting was at that time, Title IX was just coming out.
1973 or so, I think, was the year of Title IX.
And we were dealing with it because we had
in 74 or 75 because we started a sports club program and Kay Don, who was in physical education at the time, had kind of done a women's sports organization of some kind.
She came in with us with a sports club organization that we put together.
So Kay and I worked together for two or three years
heading women towards some kind of a varsity setting.
I'm not sure we knew we were doing that, but all of a sudden it happened and we had a women's varsity program and she was the athletic director for women at that time.
And that was kind of fun to kind of start that and watch it develop and then really see it come to full fruition with a women's varsity program.
So from the varsity side, that was pretty exciting stuff.
It was just fun to...
The other schools had the men's program and the women's program.
It was just fun to see here how sport developed and it wasn't so much men, women.
It was more Aggies.
The co-work program really was much bigger than the women's program.
We had a lot more women playing in the co-rec program, which is good.
It's a good socialization time.
But the women's program grew steadily and is very positive.
One of the things that I think is pretty interesting kind of relates to your question, though.
It was pretty interesting in the 70s especially to have, and this name John and I were just talking about this weekend, Debbie Pistone.
probably the best official we've ever had.
And she's out there officiating in Class A men's basketball in the mid-70s.
Now that's pretty exciting.
Guys walk on the court, and they're the top of their league in Class A men's basketball.
And this young woman comes on the court with a whistle in her mouth.
And she controls the game.
She runs the game.
Afterwards, they understand how good she is.
Did any of them try to stare her down?
Oh yeah, there's always, the problem that women face in officiating is intimidation factor.
And some of them doesn't bother at all.
Some good officials have trouble getting by that.
Have any idea where she is now?
I don't.
I don't.
We're going to look her up though.
Interesting to know where she went to.
Did, no particular incidents in women in the correct leagues?
Now, flag football was one of the major sports.
What would be the typical makeup of a team?
Was there a certain percentage of men and women that had to be on the field?
Yes.
We played around with this a little bit, but I think we ended up with six women and six men on the team.
And there could only be one, we had rules like there could be only one male-to-male pass in a four-down series.
So it forced you to pass to women or have women passing to men.
I used to play on the team.
We always had a staff team.
It was really interesting because Tara Shipley was her name.
She's related to John Coldis through Todd Shipley, who's his son-in-law.
Melissa and Todd Shipley.
And he says, I have a student who needs to work.
This is one of his Wednesday morning meetings.
I have a student who needs a job.
She's transferring from the University of Texas.
She just happened to have a job.
She came over to work.
The reason she had transferred down here is her fiance played football for the Aggies.
Her name was Ray Childress.
She not only turned out to be probably the best student worker we ever had.
She was sharp as a tack, energetic, creative, and just a hard worker.
But she was also one of the best football players we had on our staff team.
She'd never played flag football before she got out there.
She had hands of glue.
You threw it anywhere closer, she could get it.
But the Ray Childress,
He would come to every game and he would hold the downs marker on the side.
And in one game we were playing in, she was playing on defense and the ball went in the air and one of our guys, she was a pretty good size guy, was running towards the ball and she was in the way.
He didn't see it because he was looking at the ball.
He just ran right over her and she hits the ground, boom.
and Ray is on the sideline, he throws that thing down and comes chugging out, you okay, you okay?
And she was, she was fine.
I don't know how she came through it without big bruises, but it was funny to see.
He really was taking care of her.
Now, in flag football there is blocking.
It's non-contact blocking.
Oh.
And we instituted that
That was probably one of the tougher things we did in the first couple years we were here.
I think it was the second year I was here I said we're gonna, we did it in Texas.
And I had, part of the study I did when I first got into this field with Lynn Reading and Iowa State was to compare injury rates, contact blocking, non-contact blocking.
And that was a study we reported on out at Los Angeles when I met the guys from Texas.
And Texas used non-contact.
When I came down here we used full contact.
So the second year I instituted it.
And it's more like what you see in basketball, only you can use a moving screen in football.
You can't use a moving screen in basketball.
You'd call for it.
It's not like a moving screen.
You try to position yourself between, and the person rushing the passer has to go around as opposed to through you.
So it's a non-contact.
And that was one of the things that allowed more people to enjoy football.
Football was one of our, almost a minor sport until we instituted that.
It grew with everything else because women could play without fear of getting in their face.

smashed and guys good too first when I was at Iowa State the year before I went to Texas I played on a staff team there and after the first game two guys had to go get their teeth now the flag the flag that is grabbed by the opponent is placed where now the ones we use have as a flag there's a belt and it has
Flag on each side and one in the back.
Oh, so one at each hip and one at the back.
And if you grab one of the... Flags and the whole belt comes off.
Okay.
Okay.
In terms of the co-ed sports, which ones were the most popular co-eds?
Flag football and softball.
And softball.
Slow-pitch softball.
Slow-pitch, which means the ball is pitched up and then down.
Big arc, big arc kind of.
Any fast-pitch softball at all?
We probably had the biggest fast pitch lease in the country.
But I think the last time we really offered it was 7879 and 734567 and along in there we had
Quite a bit of fast pitch.
Men and women or?
Primarily men.
Primarily men.
Fast pitch for women really didn't get started until after, really after my daughter had graduated.
That's new to me too.
Yeah, that's about 87.
Have there been any examples of an intramural participant going on to varsity sports?
There are and I wish I could remember the name right now.
We had a
A kid who played basketball in Emeralds and Shelby actually picked him up way back then.
I think that's the only one that I can think of.
I think we had one in Texas too when I was there.
Which coaches, varsity coaches, were the most helpful to y'all in whatever sports?
For the most part, we dealt with Billy Pickard on facilities, because he had some hand in managing all the facilities.
You know, Edward Millard was a good guy to work with.
He really was.
And R.C.
was really good to work with in football.
Mark Johnson.
We use this facility every year.
Just a gentleman of the guy.
I don't think we've all been there.
We've enjoyed a good relationship with all the coaches.
I can't think of any specific incidents that's been a problem.
All right, let's go then from the 70s, move forward.
Describe how things changed.
were modified.
Well, the basic change was going from strictly an intramural program, which was designed to provide competition, on-campus competition for Aggies.
And we grew that just about as big as it could grow.
We were filling every space we had with sports activities.
And what that created was a lack of opportunity for people to drop in and shoot hoops or play racquetball or whatever.
We had classes that went essentially from eight to five in all the facilities we had.
And we had intramurals that went from five to midnight.
And there was two or three or four years that we were going until 2 a.m. with our building being open.
And we were playing intramurals until 2 a.m. on a regular basis.
We were just so packed with stuff.
So our focus became one of trying to figure a way to create facilities.
And we had built a lot of physical activity facilities that were primarily designed for physical education.
And we started talking to the student body about building a recreation center similar to one that was built at Texas Tech in 1980, one that was built at Purdue in 1957, was probably the first one.
But that whole

genre of buildings started evolving and really evolving and we think you know we've got the jam in the country right now this particular facility but we started talking to their students about that and in 1987 let's do it they said let's do it now and that's when we had the vote the original referendum that said we're going to charge ourselves 50 to build this building

all right and during during these years of transition and change which sports which activities compared to capability to handle which were the most over popular and the least compare the extremes well most
popular intramural sport was the sports ebb and flow in popularity was softball.
Slow pitch softball went from being in the mid 70s, probably 200 teams.
We were right at 120 teams in 74.
In 1979, we had 810 teams enter the tournament.
We didn't have a single lighted field on campus.
So we were trying to figure out how to do that.
But we did have about 25 fields at that time.
We put backstops up any place you could find bloody grass, we had a backstop up.
So that was really popular.
In tennis, we went to about 1,200 different participants in a tennis tournament at one time.
Now it's down to around 200.
So the sports kind of ebb and flow.

popularity but I think the main thing that happened though is we kept saying that there there was a need for facility where people could come and play at their leisure participate at their leisure on their schedule not on our schedule and the thing that happened has the one in 1994-95 our head count of people using our program was 250,000 in 1995-96 when we opened this building it was 1,250,000
just in this building.
So we know that there was a need for people to have a place to go recreate, and this building filled that need.
That was probably the massive change.
The other thing that happened with this building that we had intramurals, which was our biggest program, and we were reaching 48% of the student body in intramurals.
Intramurals is primarily focused in men.
Probably 90% of the participants in intramurals are men.
Now when?
Men.
Now?
Now.
Then and now.
Oh.
It's always been that way.
Okay.
What happened when we opened this building is we were able to accommodate activities that women enjoy participating in.
And if you look now, instead of our participants being 90%

men 10% women it's 52% men 48% women so it's almost exactly the same as the enrollment it is if you look at it it's going to be exactly the same because we're reaching 70 to 75 percent of the student body every semester so we're not going to vary from
